SIMPLE: brim
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Brim
<hw>Brim</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>brim</ets>,
<ets>brimme</ets>, AS. <ets>brymme</ets> edge, border; akin to Icel.
<ets>barmr</ets>, Sw. <ets>br⟦aum⟧m</ets>, Dan. <ets>br⟦ae⟧mme</ets>, G.
<ets>brame</ets>, <ets>br⟦aum⟧me</ets>. Possibly the same word as AS.
<ets>brim</ets> surge, sea, and properly meaning, the line of surf at
the border of the sea, and akin to L. <ets>fremere</ets> to roar,
murmur. Cf. <er>Breeze</er> a fly.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The rim,
border, or upper edge of a cup, dish, or any hollow vessel used for
holding anything.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Saw I that insect on this goblet's <qex>brim</qex>⟦br⟧
I would remove it with an anxious pity.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The edge or margin, as of a fountain, or of the
water contained in it; the brink; border.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The feet of the priests that bare the ark were dipped in the
<qex>brim</qex> of the water.</q> <rj><qau>Josh. iii. 15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The rim of a hat.</def>
<rj><au>Wordsworth.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Brim</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Brim
<hw>Brim</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Brimmed</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Brimming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To be full to the brim.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>brimming</xex> stream.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To brim over</b></col> <mark>(literally or
figuratively)</mark>, <cd>to be so full that some of the contents flows
over the brim; as, a cup <xex>brimming over</xex> with wine; a man
<xex>brimming over</xex> with fun.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Brim</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Brim
<hw>Brim</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To fill to the brim, upper edge, or
top.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Arrange the board and <qex>brim</qex> the glass.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Brim</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Brim
<hw>Brim</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Fierce; sharp; cold. See
<er>Breme</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Brimful</ent>⟦br⟧
